Homework Questions:

  1. Calculate the population mean and standard deviation for each quantitative random variable (height, weight, age, number of zombies killed, and years of education). NOTE: You will not want to use the built in var() and sd() commands as these are for samples.

Height:

First, I want to make a vector that only includes all of the heights. To do so, I will use the code below:

h <- c(d$height)
head(h)
## [1] 62.88951 67.80277 72.12908 66.78484 64.71832 71.24326

Looks like this worked! The first six elements it gave back match the first six from the "height’ column in our original table.

Next, I will find the mean of this vector, using the mean() function built in to R:

h_mean <- mean(h)
h_mean
## [1] 67.6301

This answer also makes sense, looking briefly over the overall data.

Next, we will find the population standard deviation for height. For this, we will use the sd() function in R, to find the sample standard deviation first:

h_sd <- sd(h)
h_sd
## [1] 4.310126

Now, to find the population standard deviation, we will take this result and multiply it by the square root of (N-1)/N in which N is the number of values for height:

h_psd <- function(h){h_sd*sqrt((length(h)-1)/length(h))}
h_psd(h)
## [1] 4.30797

As we can see, this is close to the number we got back when using sd() only, but this is now more accurate to describe the standard deviation for the entire population instead of just a sample from the population.

We can next do this for each of the other quantitative random variables:

First, we make a vector from just the ‘weight’ column from the original data frame:

Next, we find the mean:

This answer looks good! Next up, is sample standard deviation so we can find population standard deviation:

Ok, now we can put this into the population standard deviation function:

w_psd <- function(w){w_sd*sqrt((length(w)-1)/length(w))}

  1. Use {ggplot} to make boxplots of each of these variables by gender.

First off, this is an interesting population in which every person identifies as either male or female. While I am not one for people having to identify by a strict gender binary, we will go with it for this exercise.

As far as coding, at first, I think I made this way too hard, thinking I would need to write functions into the {ggplot} function. But, then I realized that this is part of the awesomeness of {ggplot}, that it has built-in functions already and knows what to do with the data when you ask it to create a boxplot based on specific variables. After looking through older modules, this is what I came up with:

Height

library(ggplot2)
height_gender <- ggplot(data=d, aes(x=gender, y=height)) #this means I am pulling from the data frame "d" and that the variables for my x axis will be pulled from the column marked "gender" and grouped by each category found, in this case, male and female, and that my y axis variables will be pulled from the column marked "height"
height_gender <- height_gender + geom_boxplot() #this tells R that we specifically want a boxplot
height_gender <- height_gender + theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=90)) #each element of the X axis will be at a 90 degree angle. 
height_gender <- height_gender + ylab("Height") #this means the y axis will be labeled "Height"
height_gender <- height_gender + xlab("Gender") #this means the x axis will be labeled "Gender"
height_gender <- height_gender + ggtitle("Height by Gender") #this means the label at the top of plot will be "Height by Gender"
height_gender

This looks pretty good! Not sure why the title is not centered, but all the elements are there. Also, probably do not need to have “Female” and “Male” at a 90 degree angle, but it is cool to know how to do this for making a box plot that has a large number of x axis variables.

Now we can do the same for the other variables:

  1. Using histograms and Q-Q plots, check whether the quantitative variables seem to be drawn from a normal distribution. qqnorm(h, main= "QQplot for Height")
qqline(h, col = "gray") #Makes a Q-Q line to see how the points fall on this line, and the color of the line is gray

hist(h, main = "Histogram for Height", xlab = "Height") #code for a histogram along with the main title of the graph and the x-axis label

  1. Now use the sample() function to sample ONE subset of 30 zombie survivors (without replacement) from this population and calculate the mean and sample standard deviation for each variable. Also estimate the standard error for each variable, and construct the 95% confidence interval for each mean. Note that for the variables that are not drawn from the normal distribution, you may need to base your estimate of the CIs on slightly different code than for the normal.

Ok, let’s try this for our first variable, which is Height:

library(sciplot)
h_sample_se <- se(h_sample)
h_sample_se
## [1] 0.7054463

For the confidence intervals, we will do:

upper_h <- h_sample_mean + qnorm(0.975) * h_sample_se
lower_h <- h_sample_mean + qnorm(0.025) * h_sample_se
h_sample_ci <- (c(lower_h, upper_h))
h_sample_ci
## [1] 66.2364 69.0017

Ok, now let’s try bootstrapping for the CIs:

set <- NULL # sets up a dummy variable to hold our 10000 simulations
n <- 30
for (i in 1:1000){
    set[i] <- mean(sample(k, n, replace=TRUE))
}
quantile(set, c(0.025, 0.975))
##     2.5%    97.5% 
## 2.400000 3.633333

These answers seem to make sense from what we know about the patterns we have already seen for the Number of Zombies Killed variable.
